<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Energy and Climate Change Committee:</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="color:#31849b; font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by British Gas (HOT46)</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="color:#31849b; font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Executive Summary</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">British Gas is the leading supplier of gas heating </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in the UK; a leading provider of renewable heating, and a leading supplier of district heating in urban housing.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We are a market leader in biomass heating, offering a complete design, installation and energy services package to domestic properties, busine</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sses and public sector customers.  We design and install ground and air source heat pumps, both directly for customers and also as a sub-contractor for larger projects in the commercial and public sector.  British Gas is one of the UK’s leading suppliers o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">f boilers and central heating, and we help our customers reduce their heating through our in-house insulation business.  There are currently more than 200 apprentices training with British Gas as boiler and heating engineers, and we have trained more than </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">5,000 apprentice engineers.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Around £1 in every £4 spent heating British homes is wasted due to poor insulation and we support continued focus on this area.  It should be recognised that energy efficiency is already lowering consumption and mitigating the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> impact of rising unit costs. In 2010 the Centre for Economic and Business Research (CEBR) gathered 74 million British Gas meter readings, and carried out a detailed analysis of a sample of four million - the largest ever independent analysis.  It found th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">at our customers cut consumption by an average 22% (£322 a year), with savings of up to 44% for those who installed more than one energy efficiency measure.  The largest impacts on natural gas consumption come from insulating cavity walls (18.3% reduction)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">; installing an A-rated energy efficient boiler (18.0% reduction) and by insulating lofts (13.8% reduction). </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Weather adjusted, the average British Gas dual fuel bill has risen by 4% per annum from 2006-2011, broadly in line with inflation. We believe our</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> customers have the potential to save over £3 billion over the next five years if they invest in energy efficiency measures.   </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">British Gas supports the Government’s aims for ECO and Green Deal in improving the energy efficiency of Britain’s housing stock</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, reducing carbon emissions and lowering energy bills for customers. We believe the design and structure of both programmes can be improved.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-transform:uppercase">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt; text-transform:uppercase"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We believe that biomass can play a key role in both domestic and commercial heating in parallel with heat pump </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">deployment and we therefore advocate support for both technologies.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Renewable Heat Incentive is starting to work for small and medium-scale heat. However the budget allocation for biomass has reduced against that indicated in the 2012 DECC consultatio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n.  This is causing a premature degression of RHI levels in medium biomass, a technology that is cost-effective in meeting renewable energy targets. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">British Gas supports the proposed increase in ground source and large biomass. We also support the introd</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">uction of commercial air source heat pumps. To ensure that the non-domestic RHI remains cost-effective, we propose that the proportion of the RHI budget allocated to solid biomass of all sizes is increased.  Commercial air source is an important technology</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> but should be encouraged only with caution when on-gas grid until grid and power capacity issues are resolved.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We are disappointed that the 2015/16 RHI is £430m, only £6m more than the allocation for 2014/15.  This is approximately a 20% to 30% decrease </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">compared to the original trajectory of spend, and risks the UK not meeting 2020 targets for renewable heat.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt; text-transform:uppercase"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Small and medium size district heating networks also have a role to play. We welcome Government recognition that heat networks need to be part of t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he future UK heat arena and note that ECO is an important mechanism to fund domestic district heating. We see opportunities to increase the cost effectiveness of combined energy efficiency and district heating projects under ECO.  However, we believe that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the barriers to deployment of large retrofit heating networks (and their potential cost) are significantly greater. We need to see funding support mechanisms for these large-scheme with structures similar to other large infrastructure projects. We are work</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing with industry to create guidelines for consumer protection.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-transform:uppercase">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt; text-transform:uppercase"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We therefore advocate at least as much focus on small and medium size networks as large city centre networks due to their much lower cost and reduced complexity.  Such smaller scale networks </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are easier and cheaper to install and provide a more manageable route towards heat modernisation. We believe district heating could be a transformational technology and support its inclusion as a primary measure in the ECO CERO obligation.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">British Gas wel</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">comes the Energy and Climate Change Committee’s inquiry into Heat, which we believe is timely, and we are pleased to respond.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#31849b; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Question 1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#31849b; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Is the government taking the right approach to reduce heat energy demand?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Heat energy demand in the domestic sector is predominantly being driven through the supplier ECO programme and the Green Deal.  There remains considerable opportunity for cost-effective energy efficiency in the UK housing stock, primarily in the form of lo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ft insulation (~5.7m) and cavity wall insulation (~3.8m). and upgrading to condensing boilers (~9.5m).</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">British Gas supports the Government’s aims for ECO in improving the energy efficiency of Britain’s housing stock, reducing carbon emissions and lowering</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> energy bills for customers. However, ECO is likely to cost more than Government estimates and we believe the design and structure of ECO can be simply but substantially improved.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In particular we believe the first ECO period should be extended which co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">uld help to reduce costs in line with Government’s impact assessment.  The first </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ECO period has to be delivered over a very sh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ort timescale (2 ¼ years to March 20</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">15) and delivery is complicated by a number of sub-targets.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We would also like to see bette</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r transparency in ECO brokerage, loft and easy cavity wall insulations included as acceptable CERO measures, and the definition of inefficient boilers within the Affordable Warmth sub-obligation simplified.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We are supportive of the Green Deal programme </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and believe it can make a significant impact in delivering energy efficiency measures to UK homes.  We support changes to the Green Deal framework to boost consumer demand, and to streamline processes.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Building regulations also have an important role to p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lay and we would support a more ambitious approach in this regard.   We also believe that the legal minimum energy efficiency standard for homes rented from a landlord that is being implemented from April 2018 should be brought forward, and that this stand</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ard should also extend to houses in multiple occupation.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#31849b; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Question 2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#31849b; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What progress is the government making on reducing the demand for heat?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="color:#31849b; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">No comment</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#31849b; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Question 3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#31849b; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Biomass is deemed a key fuel for heat production from both the cost and perspectives.</span><span style="color:#31849b; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span><span style="color:#31849b; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> What should be done to </span><span style="color:#31849b; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ensure methods of calculating biomass GHG balance represents an accurate picture?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We support an increased role for biomass heat and CHP especially for commercial, industrial and district heating installations in the 2020/2030 timeframe, although we believ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e this role will be limited by the price/supply of sustainable biomass fuel towards the end of this period. We agree with current DECC plans to ensure that biomass is appropriately sourced and delivers significant carbon savings. We believe that applicatio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ns with proportionately high conversion efficiencies (heat and CHP) should be encouraged as a priority.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Substantial work has been carried out by the European Commission and European Environment Agency to more carefully assess the appropriate types of biom</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ass which should be used for heat production.  This can inform this complex area.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#31849b; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Question 4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#31849b; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">There are sustainability guidelines for biomass, do these go far enough?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">DECC have issued sustainability reporting guidelines for biomass electricity and advised that these</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> will also apply to biomass heat.  We have not yet, however, seen the detail of the biomass heat sustainability guidelines and therefore can not comment further at this stage.  In particular, we are keen to understand the detailed guidance for fuel supplie</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rs to biomass heat plants under 1 MW to clarify that this is practical and workable.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#31849b; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Question 5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#31849b; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What will the local environmental impact (for example air pollution) be from the use heat generation in urban areas, for example, heat pumps?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The UK Government </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">roadmap anticipates that urban heat will be produced from a combination of district heating, gas and heat pumps (all types). Commercial biomass </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is also anticipated to be an important part of this supply for commercial and district heating.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The RHI regulat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ions on emissions standards have been substantially tightened for biomass heating, and are due to come into force in September 2013.  Existing regulations currently require Local Authorities to approve flue design and emission levels for the installation o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">f biomass plant based on local considerations. The combination of these regulations should be carefully monitored to confirm that they are sufficient and appropriate.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#31849b; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Question 6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#31849b; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What are the relative merits of using gas to directly provide space heating compared to </span><span style="color:#31849b; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">centralised electricity production plus domestic heat pumps?</span><span style="color:#31849b; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span><span style="color:#31849b; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We broadly support the Government’s trajectory for low carbon heat in the 2020/2030 timeframe.  We anticipate that gas will remain the predominant source of space heating, supplemented increas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ingly by renewable off-gas grid and district heating for dense urban applications over this timeframe.  We agree that the displacement of electric heating and oil should be a priority.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">On-grid, we believe that there should be increased focus on increasing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the efficiency of gas heating using hybrid electric heat pump/gas boilers which will be supported by the domestic RHI, and trialling emerging technologies such as micro CHP and domestic gas heat pumps.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We do not support high levels of use of electric-onl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">y heat pumps on-gas grid in the 2020/30 timeframe except for new build due to issues relating to peak grid capacity, and the relatively high carbon content of the grid.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We broadly agree with the findings in the DECC “Future of Heating: meeting the challen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ge” publication of March 2013 (pg 5) that suggested the “extreme peak” heat demand required on the coldest winter days will not be cost-effective to meet with electricity due partly to the increased costs of providing the generation capacity and the reinfo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rcements required of the power grid.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The UK has the most modern gas grid in Europe, and a great geographical location to access future gas supplies.  We strongly advocate that there should be a continuing role for gas for a long transitional period.  Biog</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">as could lower the carbon intensity of the grid, whilst continuing to provide a reasonably low cost heating source </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for domestic and commercial buildings.  Micro CHP gas boilers offer a readily available route to make efficient use of this resource for the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">coming decades.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We also see considerable potential for gas heat pumps.  Their efficiency and high carbon savings make them a very attractive transition technology that would smoothly integrate with the UK’s existing gas infrastructure without the impact </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on peak loading on the local electricity grid seen with other heat pump technologies.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We support in principle DECC’s ambition for district heating in dense urban areas. We note that ECO is a potential substantial funding source for retrofit schemes in lin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e with DECC’s heat strategy.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We believe district heating could be a transformational technology and support its inclusion as a primary measure in the ECO CERO obligation. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We are pleased that DECC has secured funding for feasibility studies for larger city</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> centre schemes.  We note that there is currently no funding mechanism for larger commercial schemes and would support work in this area.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="color:#31849b; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#31849b; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Question 7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#31849b; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Why is community heating/CHP not more common in the UK?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The UK has had low-cost gas networks for many years that have provided the  majority of urban heat. There remains inadequate funding for long-term infrastructure investments in district heating networks.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="color:#31849b; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#31849b; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Question 8.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#31849b; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What are the lock-in, costs and GHG savings from th</span><span style="color:#31849b; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">e promotion of different forms of domestic heating solution? </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">District heating in conjunction with biomass, energy from waste and waste industrial heat is a good technology for use in dense urban domestic and commercial applications.  It can also be deplo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">yed for gas and gas CHP schemes in the short term.  Energy centres can be modified over time to facilitate different forms of generation, there-by preventing lock-in of any particular technology.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In contrast, there is a danger of increasing peak electrici</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ty demand if heat pumps are rolled-out at scale in advance of grid capacity increase and a reduction in the carbon content of the grid.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We note that the GHG saving are highly dependent on the counterfactual that is assumed, and that therefore it is not a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">simple task to compare and contrast GHG savings across the different technologies.  As an example, putting heat pumps and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">biomass into off-gas grid properties generates higher carbon GHG savings than into on-gas properties as heating oil has a higher carbo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n intensity that gas.  It is therefore sensible to target off-grid consumers with these technologies first.  However, heat pumps GHG savings are dependent on the grid intensity of electricity and so considerable care needs to be taken not to over-incentivi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">se them too early, before a high level of grid decarbonisation</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#31849b; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Question 9.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#31849b; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Should the government take any further any specific actions in relation to cooling?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">No comment</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-transform:uppercase">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#31849b; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Question 10.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#31849b; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Why does the RHI not seem to promote heat pumps successfully?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The RHI does not promote commerc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ial ground heat pumps because this is a relatively expensive technology for retrofit heating compared to biomass.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="38" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The original DECC guidance only permitted the net heat from heating and cooling applications to be taken into account when deciding RHI payme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nts.  This has now been corrected and higher rates have been proposed from Spring 2014.  Commercial air source heat pumps will be supported under the RHI from Spring 2014. This should accelerate the roll-out of commercial heat pumps.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#31849b; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Question 11.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#31849b; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How successful will </span><span style="color:#31849b; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">the RHI be when rolled out to households?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="39" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We believe that the domestic RHI has been well designed for households off-gas grid, although household installations over 45kW are not currently supported. We believe that a majority of installations will be heat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> pumps. This is appropriate off-grid.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#31849b; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Question 12.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#31849b; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Thermal storage is a potential useful method of balancing electricity/energy demand both diurnally and annually.</span><span style="color:#31849b; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span><span style="color:#31849b; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> What is government policy doing to promote thermal storage, and should it do more/different?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="40" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Thermal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> stores are of use for balancing demand over short periods (within the day). In addition they are useful for ground source heating and cooling applications to improve heat pump CoP.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="41" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Currently, a considerable amount of diurnal thermal storage takes the for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">m of hot water tanks. We note that the increasing trend to exchange standard boilers with tanks for combi boilers with no tanks means that overall the opportunity for diurnal heat storage is declining in households. This may have implications for the futur</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e mass roll-out of electric heat-pumps which generally will require the consumer to have a hot water tank.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>